        "theme":  "Agents",
        "summary":  "Zscaler testing across 26 LLMs found that four models ΓÇö including Gemini-2.5-pro ΓÇö are vulnerable to indirect prompt injection attacks, where hidden instructions embedded in web content manipulate agent behavior to take unauthorized actions such as processing fraudulent payments. The vulnerability is described as architectural rather than behavioral: transformer-based reasoning cannot cleanly separate untrusted content from trusted instructions when both occupy the same context window. Analysts warn that the same technique applied to agents authorized for procurement, expense processing, vendor onboarding, or trading could cause catastrophic financial losses.",
        "execSummary":  "Indirect prompt injection is now a documented, tested production risk for enterprise AI agents ΓÇö not a theoretical concern ΓÇö and the attack surface is architectural, meaning it cannot be fully patched through model updates or prompt engineering alone. For customer-support leaders deploying agents that access external content (emails, web pages, customer-uploaded documents), every piece of untrusted content that enters the agent\u0027s context window is a potential attack vector for hijacking agent actions. The most concerning finding is that Gemini-2.5-pro showed weaker IPI resistance than Gemini-3.1-flash-lite, meaning higher-capability models are not inherently safer. The immediate mitigation posture is to restrict agent permissions to the minimum required scope, log every tool call and data access, and isolate untrusted content from the instruction context where architecturally possible.",
        "vendorLean":  "Zscaler ΓÇö findings and framing originate from Zscaler\u0027s own security research and blog, positioning their security perspective as the authority.",
