        "theme":  "Platforms",
        "summary":  "NVIDIA\u0027s Vera CPU, featuring the custom Olympus core with 50% higher instructions per cycle than Grace and up to 1.2TB/s memory bandwidth, is designed for agentic AI workloads where sequential loop dependencies make per-core speed the binding constraint. Perplexity is the named early adopter, reporting approximately 1.5x faster workflow completion and 1.9x faster concurrent sandbox startup versus x86 alternatives in real coding agent workloads. The architecture targets the specific bottleneck where additional CPU cores provide no benefit because each agent step must await the prior step\u0027s completion.",
        "execSummary":  "NVIDIA Vera addresses a constraint that will become more visible as enterprises scale agentic AI: CPU single-threaded speed, not core count or GPU capacity, is often the rate limiter in agent loop performance. For enterprise infrastructure and platform teams building out AI agent compute stacks, this reframes the hardware evaluation criteria ΓÇö raw thread count matters less than per-core throughput for sequential agent workflows. Perplexity\u0027s 1.5-1.9x performance gains on real agentic coding tasks are credible production benchmarks, not synthetic lab results. Organizations planning AI infrastructure refreshes in 2026-2027 should factor agentic workload profiles into CPU architecture selection, as traditional x86 optimization assumptions may not hold.",
        "vendorLean":  "NVIDIA ΓÇö promotes Vera CPU as purpose-built for AI agent workloads, driving hardware platform differentiation for NVIDIA.",
